## 1. Oracles Donâ€™t All Tick at the Same Speed  
Chainlink feeds update on different schedules, some every hour, others only once every 24 hours.  
If you use one global freshness check, youâ€™re either:  
- Accepting stale prices (bad security), or  
- Reverting all the time (bad UX).  

ğŸ‘‰ Lesson: **Each feed should have its own heartbeat check**. Donâ€™t treat them all the same.  



## 2. stETH Isnâ€™t Like Other Tokens  
stETH is sneaky. Because of its share mechanics and rounding, you might not always receive the exact amount you try to transfer.  
If you just log the â€œamount requestedâ€ instead of the **real balance change**, your numbers drift and break things.  

This can snowball into underflows, denial of service, and even lost rewards for users.  

ğŸ‘‰ Lesson: **Always record balance differences (after - before)** when handling tokens like stETH.  



## 3. Integrations Break if You Forget About Upgrades  
Aave isnâ€™t static...pools change, versions upgrade. In Morpheus, they allowed the owner to switch pool addresses but forgot to fix approvals.  

The result?  
- Old pools kept unlimited approvals (bad security),  
- New pools had no approvals (deposits/withdrawals failed).  

ğŸ‘‰ Lesson: **Handle migrations safely.**  
- Use the official `PoolAddressProvider` to always get the current pool.  
- Or, if you set it manually, revoke old approvals and approve the new one.  



## 4. Rewards Can End, Yield Doesnâ€™t  
This one really stood out.  
In Morpheus, the contract stopped updating balances whenever rewards = 0. The problem? Rewards might stop, but yield doesnâ€™t.  

So stakers were still earning yield, but they couldnâ€™t withdraw it because the system thought nothing changed.  

ğŸ‘‰ Lesson: **Never tie yield accounting directly to rewards.**  
Even if rewards are over, users must still be able to access their yield.  



## Final Thoughts  
What I learnt from these findings is simple: **details matter**.  
- One heartbeat setting caused stale oracles.  
- A few wei difference in stETH broke balances.  
- One missing approval broke Aave deposits.  
- One early return locked yield forever.  

ğŸ‘‰ Big picture: Small oversights can cause huge problems.  
Thatâ€™s what Iâ€™ll keep in mind when auditing or building smart contracts.